ical models - folklorist, anthropological, psychoanalytical - that can be used to analyse cultures of transition in the history and literature of fourteenth-century Europe. Ranging over a wide variety of texts, from chronicles to romances, from priests' manuals to courtesy books, from state records to the writings of Chaucer, Gower and Froissart, the contributors identify and analyse medieval attitudes to the process of change in lifecycle, status,gender and power. A substantive introduction by Miri Rubin draws together the ideas and materials discussed in the book to illustrate the relevance and importance of anthropology to the study of medieval culture. Contributors: JOEL BURDEN, PATRICIA CULLUM, ISABEL DAVIS, JANE GILBERT, SARAH KAY, MARK ORMROD, HELEN PHILLIPS, MIRI RUBIN, SHARON WELLS. NICOLA F. McDONALD is Lecturer in Medieval Literature, the late W.M ORMROD was Professor of Medieval History, University of York.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivilization, Medievaly14th century. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Customs & Traditions.2bisacsh  aFourteenth-century Europe.  aGender.  aLifecycle.  aRites of passage.  aStatus.1 aBurden, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCullum, P. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCullum, Pat H, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilbert, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKay, H S, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKay, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDonald, Nicola F, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 